<DOC><DOCNO> AP880304-0214 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-88 0242EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   03-04 0525</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0548</SECOND><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Sales by the nation's largest general retailers wereunexpectedly slow in February, prompting worries that year-oldsluggishness in the retail sector has yet to run its course.   The nation's largest retailer, Sears, Roebuck and Co., saidThursday its sales rose 2.5 percent from February 1987. K mart saidits overall sales were up 0.8 percent, but sales at stores open atleast a year fell 1.6 percent.   ``The results do not bode well for the economy,'' said FredWintzer, a retail industry analyst for the investment firm Alex.Brown andamp; Sons Inc.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Led by industry-leader General Motors Corp.,automakers sold 25 percent more domestic cars and light trucks inlate February than a year ago, the car companies have reported.   GM said Thursday its sales during the last third of Februarywere the highest for late February since 1972.   In the seven selling days from Feb. 21-29, GM sold 127,549domestic cars, up 33.4 percent from a year ago, and 59,709 domesticlight trucks, up 46.2 percent from a year ago.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chrysler Motors Corp. has decided not to sell itsAcustar Inc. parts-making subsidiary but says it will close or sellfour plants within the next 18 months.   The No. 3 automaker said Thursday that the four plants _ AmplexVan Wert in Van Wert, Ohio, Trenton Chemical in suburban Detroit,Detroit Forge and Detroit Trim _ employ about 2,000 workers.   The United Auto Workers union said it was pleased by thedecision but urged Chrysler to find ways not to close the fourplants.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Improvements in the nation's efficiency inchurning out goods and services slowed by almost half last yeardespite revised figures showing higher output in the the fourthquarter, the government said.   The Labor Department said Thursday that productivity amongnon-farm businesses responsible for three-fourths of the nation'seconomic activity rose at an annual rate of 0.3 percent in thefourth quarter in contrast to a deterioration of 0.2 percentreported in preliminary figures last month.   The revisions raised the productivity improvement for the entireyear from 0.8 percent to 0.9 percent, slightly more than half the1.6 percent gain of 1986, despite the lowest hourly labor costincreases in more than four decades.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Democratic-controlled House laborstandards subcommittee has voted along party lines to increase theminimum wage from $3.35 to $4.65 an hour over the next three years.   The 6-3 vote Thursday came on a measure to raise the minimumwage 50 cents an hour on Jan. 1, 1989 and 40 cents an hour each ofthe following years.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Reagan's sanctions against Japaneseelectronics imports have halted computer chip ``dumping'' but havefailed to boost sales of U.S. chips in Japan, according to anindustry group.   The Semiconductor Industry Association said Thursday that by theend of 1987, the U.S. share of the Japanese chip market was 10percent, up only slightly from the 9 percent share that existedwhen the sanctions were announced last April.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>